<TABLE BORDER=0 cellpadding=4 border=0 cellspacing=1 WIDTH="95%"><TR bgcolor="#D5E6E1"><TD COLSPAN=2><CENTER><FONT SIZE="2" COLOR="#000080" FACE="Verdana, Arial">T O P I C  &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; R E V I E W</font></CENTER></TD></TR><TR bgcolor="#dedfdf"><TD valign=top><FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Verdana, Arial">Spawrhawk</FONT></TD><TD><FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Verdana, Arial">I know the items (cazic brain, 7th Coldain Prayer Shawl, ect.). I want to know the mana per tick. <P>I have heard that Flowing thought I is ONE mana per tick. I read on various sites that it is TEN mana per tick. <P>Which one is it? <P>Thank you in advance. <P>Spawrhawk Wormwood<BR>54 Vicar of Fennin Ro</FONT></TD></TR><TR bgcolor="#f7f7f7"><TD valign=top><FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Verdana, Arial">Aiien</FONT></TD><TD><FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Verdana, Arial">Flowing Thought I is 1 mana per tick, Flowing Thought II is 2 mana per tick. There used to be Flowing Thought effects up to 10 in spdat, but all but the first three were removed. To my knowledge, no item in game uses the third, and it could also have been removed.<P>Aiien</FONT></TD></TR><TR bgcolor="#dedfdf"><TD valign=top><FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Verdana, Arial">Boanerges</FONT></TD><TD><FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Verdana, Arial">The recent GM wizard event on all servers yielded an artifact with 10 mana per tick...<P>------------------<BR>Boanerges Thundercry<BR>Erudite Templar of Prexus<BR><A HREF="http://www.cohort.cc" TARGET=_blank>Cohort Chalybeius</A><BR>Cazic Thule Server</FONT></TD></TR><TR bgcolor="#f7f7f7"><TD valign=top><FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Verdana, Arial">Cayleu</FONT></TD><TD><FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Verdana, Arial">I have the 7th shawl, and have done some work timing mana regen with and without it. Flowing thought 1 is definitely only 1 mana per tick. If it was any higher, I would have noticed ; )</FONT></TD></TR><TR bgcolor="#dedfdf"><TD valign=top><FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Verdana, Arial">Spawrhawk</FONT></TD><TD><FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Verdana, Arial">::sigh:: <P>Thanks for your responses. I feared that it was true but now I know...<P>Does anyone know with SoL (the irony, oh I love the irony...) if the casters are going to be thrown a bone with that expansion?<P>I had heard a few rumors but I want to know what you thought.<P>Thanks in advance.<P>Spawrhawk Wormwood<BR>54 Vicar of Fennin Ro</FONT></TD></TR><TR bgcolor="#f7f7f7"><TD valign=top><FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Verdana, Arial">Mirriana_00</FONT></TD><TD><FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Verdana, Arial">I believe VI said there would be things you could exchange xp for at 60, like give an NPC one bar of xp and you get to cast spells 1% faster.<P>Not sure if it is going to make it in, but they said it once.</FONT></TD></TR><TR bgcolor="#dedfdf"><TD valign=top><FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Verdana, Arial">Seolta</FONT></TD><TD><FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Verdana, Arial">Quote"The recent GM wizard event on all servers yielded an artifact with 10 mana per tick..."End Quote<P>Boanerges is talking about the Scepter of Al'Kabor <A HREF="http://mmo.gameznet.com/eq/new/equipment/lazy/scepterofalkabor.shtml" TARGET=_blank>http://mmo.gameznet.com/eq/new/equipment/lazy/scepterofalkabor.shtml</A> <P>"Al'Kabor's Expansive Mind" is an innate 10pt per tick mana regen that works whenever the stick is equipped. As an innate effect, it stacks with other mana regen spells.<BR>This item is also an "Artifact" ie. one maximum per server. <P>I doubt we will see any Flowing Thought 10 items dropping from normal mobs ever. For that matter, i'd be really suprised to see values above Flowing Though 3 on anything but GM Event items and Artifacts.<P>Also, for the record, if you have 2 items with the Flowing Thought effect, only the one with the highest value will affect you(similar to the way haste items work). IE they don't stack with each other.<P><BR>------------------<BR>Seolta the Strategist<BR>Drunken Mick of the 60th Pint<BR>Blood of the Spider<BR>The Rathe - Team Powerfire <A HREF="http://www.drow.org" TARGET=_blank>http://www.drow.org</A> <P>[This message has been edited by Seolta (edited 08-12-2001).]<p>[This message has been edited by Seolta (edited 08-12-2001).]</FONT></TD></TR><TR bgcolor="#f7f7f7"><TD valign=top><FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Verdana, Arial">Niccy</FONT></TD><TD><FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Verdana, Arial"> <BLOCKQUOTE><font size="1" face="Verdana, Arial">quote:</font><HR>Originally posted by Mirriana_00:<BR>I believe VI said there would be things you could exchange xp for at 60, like give an NPC one bar of xp and you get to cast spells 1% faster.<BR><HR></BLOCKQUOTE><P><A HREF="http://gamespot.com/gamespot/stories/previews/0,10869,2780291-4,00.html" TARGET=_blank>This GameSpot preview</A> has this to say:<P> <BLOCKQUOTE><font size="1" face="Verdana, Arial">quote:</font><HR><BR>At this point in development, a lot of the upcoming additions to gameplay have not been solidified, but in addition to a new race and a new class, there will be other advancement options for players who are continuing to level up their existing characters. <B>It was mentioned at the E3 demonstration and more recently at the Minneapolis Fan Faire that players with level 60 characters may be able to trade some experience for additional skills or perhaps complete quests to acquire new titles and a new set of skills.</B> Not much is known about this yet, as the development team has to determine how all the options will affect class and gameplay balance, but it would be a welcome addition to be able to individualize characters to a greater degree. Currently in EverQuest, it's rather difficult to really distinguish, say, one level 60 wizard from another other than differences in equipment. Also, more quests will be added for all levels of play, and there will be a new set of epic class armor in addition to the current three existing variations of epic quest armor found in Velious. <P><BR>Casters will be able to focus their spells against monsters like these. <P>In addition, the Luclin expansion will offer more options to the caster classes. Specifically, a whole range of caster focus items will be available from level 1 to 60; these items will actually focus caster abilities. <B>A caster may find, for example, a robe that causes spells to do more damage, last longer, cast faster, or heal more hit points.</B> Such items make casters more useful and more powerful much in the same way that currently existing pieces of special armor or particularly powerful weapons cast spells or have special effects for the melee classes. Currently in the game, certain fighter-usable items can cast damage spells or add permanent effects like haste, which allow melee fighters to attack more quickly, but there is no equivalent haste item for casters. <BR><HR></BLOCKQUOTE><P><BR></FONT></TD></TR></TABLE>
</FONT>
